AB  - TO THE EDITOR—We read with interest the article by Kalil et al [1]
published in the 15 January 2014 issue of Clinical Infectious
Diseases, and would like to comment on the issue of time to
appropriate antibiotics and also to share findings from a
complementary study completed at our center. We commend Kalil et al on
their robust study design and analysis, as well as their novel
conclusions. As part of an institutional quality assessment activity,
we retrospectively determined the timing of appropriate antibiotics
and associated factors in a cohort of 111 consecutive solid organ
transplant recipients with gram-negative bacteremia from March 2008 to
December 2013 at the University of Washington Medical Center.
Eighty-seven patients (78.4%) met sepsis criteria at the time of blood
culture was drawn, and 65 (58.6%) met criteria for severe sepsis. As
in the study by Kalil et al, we found a relatively high rate of
appropriate antibiotics within 24 hours of blood cultures being drawn
(78.4%) and a similarly low 28-day mortality rate of 9.1% (Table 1).
Our study was not powered to determine if the time to appropriate
antibiotics was associated with mortality in this cohort. Because
multiple prior studies of patients with sepsis have demonstrated an
association between shorter time to appropriate antibiotics and lower
mortality [2–5], we are interested to know whether the authors are
able to assess this parameter in their models. As many large
transplant centers have institutional clinical pathways and guidelines
for management of sepsis in transplant patients, and because there is
often a heightened index of suspicion for infection in
immunocompromised patients, we wonder whether the lower mortality in
solid organ transplant patients reported by Kalil et al could, in
part, be explained by a shorter time to initiation of appropriate
antibiotics.
