AB  - OBJECTIVES

Considering the difficulty of diagnosing catheter-related bloodstream
infection (CRBSI), Koo Foundation Sun Yat-Sen Cancer Center uses
differential time to positivity (DTP) as a hospital-wide approach to
improve the diagnosis of CRBSI in febrile patients with indwelling
central venous catheters (CVCs). This study describes the result of a
hospital-wide use of DTP in a real practice setting.

METHODS

During January 2003-August 2007, 142 positive paired blood cultures
from 125 patients without infection focus other than CVC were
included. These were evaluated by DTP and semi-quantitative catheter
culture (SQCC) to confirm the diagnosis of CRBSI, and were further
divided into two groups: confirmed (either by DTP or SQCC) and
non-confirmed CRBSI (neither DTP nor SQCC positive).

RESULTS

Fifty-nine point two percent (84/142) of episodes were confirmed as
CRBSI, of which DTP was positive in 83.3% (n=70). Non-confirmed CRBSI
was associated with hematologic malignancy, neutropenia status,
previous antibiotics exposure and a lower CVC removal rate.

CONCLUSIONS

A hospital-wide approach of DTP was practical and feasible in
improving the diagnosis of CRBSI in a real practice setting.
