AB  - Introduction/Hypothesis: The timely administration of broad-spectrum
antibiotics with activity against Pseudomonas aeruginosa and other
multi-drug resistant Gram-negative rods (GNRs) is a life-saving
therapy for critically ill patients with sepsis. While the CDC
advocates for a review of the indication, duration and choice of
antibiotics at 48hrs, the optimal timing of de-escalation in patients
with negative cultures to narrower spectrum antibiotics, like
ceftriaxone, remains unknown. Time to culture positivity has
previously been used to study the optimal timing for deescalation in
gram-positive cocci. We tested the hypothesis that cultures will
identify GNRs that ultimately demonstrate resistance to ceftriaxone
within 48 hours, allowing safe de-escalation at this time point.
Methods: Using the EHR, we evaluated patients whose respiratory and
blood cultures grew ceftriaxone resistant GNRs as a secondary analysis
of the 15,802 critically ill adults enrolled in the Isotonic Solutions
and Major Adverse Renal Events Trial (SMART), a pragmatic,
clusterrandomised, multiple-cross over trial of intravenous fluids.
Results: A total of 524 respiratory cultures from 304 (1.92%) patients
had growth of GNRs, of which 284 (54.2%) had resistance to
ceftriaxone. A total of 376 blood cultures from 311 (1.97%) patients
grew GNRs, of which 70 (18.6%) had resistance to ceftriaxone. For
cultures with resistance to ceftriaxone, the median (IQR) time from
collection to identification of GNRs was 33 (25-41) hours for
respiratory cultures and 21 (1831) hours for blood cultures. By 48
hours after collection, 87% of respiratory cultures and 85% of blood
cultures that would ultimately grow GNRs resistant to ceftriaxone had
demonstrated growth. At 72 hours, 98% of respiratory and 94% of blood
cultures demonstrated such growth. Delayed growth of respiratory and
blood cultures past 48hrs was not associated with preceding antibiotic
use (n=45, p=0.15) in a logistic regression analysis. Conclusions: In
a broad population of critically ill adults, 13% of respiratory and
15% of blood cultures ultimately growing ceftriaxone resistant GNRs
have not demonstrated growth at 48 hours. De-escalation from agents
targeting Pseudomonas aeruginosa and extended-spectrum β-lactamases
may not be advisable until cultures are negative for at least 72
hours.
