AB  - The aim of the study was to evaluate the impact of the BioFire
FilmArray Blood Culture Identification 2 (BCID2) Panel and
antimicrobial stewardship on clinical outcomes in patients with
organisms not covered by empiric regimens.

This was a single-center retrospective review comparing adults with
extended-spectrum β-lactamase (ESBL), carbapenemase (CPE), or
AmpC-producing Enterobacterales, Acinetobacter baumannii,
Stenotrophomonas maltophilia, or Enterococcus spp. bloodstream
infections before and after BCID2 implementation. The primary outcome
was time from blood culture positivity to initiation of effective
therapy. Secondary outcomes included recurrence, resistance
development, readmission, Clostridioides difficile infection, and
30-day mortality.

The final cohort included 319 patients (pre-BCID2 n = 128, post-BCID2
n = 191), with a median age of 69 years (57–81). The majority of
patients had Enterococcus spp. (44%) or ESBL Enterobacterales (41%)
infections, and most had urinary (35%) or intra-abdominal (28%)
sources. Time to effective therapy was significantly shorter
post-BCID2 (7 hours vs 4 hours, P = 0.01), particularly among those
with ESBL (40 hours vs 5 hours, P < 0.01), high-risk AmpC-producing
organism (41 hours vs 6 hours, P = 0.17), and Enterococcus faecium
infections (17 hours vs 5 hours, P = 0.067). Antimicrobial stewardship
pharmacists performed interventions more frequently post-BCID2 (34% vs
49%, P < 0.01). There were no differences between groups in secondary
outcomes.

Implementation of the BCID2 Panel in conjunction with antimicrobial
stewardship was associated with shorter time to effective therapy.
Further studies are needed to understand the impact on patient-related
outcomes.
