AB  - Introduction: Although survival from septic shock is improved when
initial antimicrobial therapy is appropriate for pathogenic isolates,
critical timing elements with respect to initial antimicrobial therapy
of septic shock have not been defined in relation to onset of
hypotension. Hypothesis: Duration of time from first onset of
recurrent/persistent hypotension to administration of effective
antimicrobial therapy is a critical determinant of survival in human
septic shock. Methods: Data was extracted from the medical records of
2600 ICU patients with septic shock. Outcome was stratified based on
time to administration of effective antimicrobial therapy,
appropriateness of initial therapy, and other therapeutic variables.
Results: Overall mortality was 52.4%. Median time to implementation of
effective antimicrobial therapy following onset of hypotension was
6.25 hrs with 19.6% of patients receiving initially inappropriate
therapy. Duration of hypotension prior to effective antimicrobial
therapy initiation was strongly correlated with outcome (p<0.0001).
Odds ratio of death increased progressively with delays in initiation
of appropriate therapy with a 5-10% decrease in survival with every
hour delay over the first 6 hrs. By the 2nd hour after onset of
hypotension, survival was significantly reduced relative to initiaton
of therapy within the first hour (p<0.05). In a multivariate model
with initial appropriateness of antimicrobials, use of 2 or more
bacteriocidal antimicrobials and severity of illness (APACHE II), time
to effective therapy remained highly predictive of outcome (p<0.0001).
Conclusions: Rapid initiation of effective antimicrobial therapy
following first onset of recurrent or persistent hypotension is a
critical determinant of outcome in human septic shock. Given the
substantial deterioration in mortality as a consequence of even modest
delays, antimicrobial administration should represent an intrinsic
resuscitative priority.
