AB  - In the present issue of Infectious Diseases, an article by S. Morioka
determined that a time to positivity (TTP) of 16 h was associated with
CoNS bacteraemia, while that of >20 h was associated with CoNS
contamination in cancer patients [1]. They have only used an
objective, non-judgmental definition for CoNS contamination to avoid
confounding bias with clinical findings. In our opinion, some factors
must be taken into consideration when definition of ‘true bacteraemia’
and contamination is assessed. Despite authors stated that nurses drew
blood at different sites in every single set, it is difficult to
ensure it in a retrospective study. Sometimes, in oncologic patients
and in real life, blood is drawn through the catheter and this could
lead to false positive results, thus it cannot be completely excluded
in a retrospective study. Proper collection of blood cultures helps to
maximize the identification of true pathogens. Otherwise, misdiagnosis
of a contamination as true infection may lead to over-use of
antibiotics [2]. Skin preparation using antiseptics is an essential
step to avoid contamination [3–5]. It is important to highlight the
need to perform surveillance programs to assess the compliance with
blood cultures practices and to perform continuous education and
training to the personnel ensuring that blood cultures are obtained
following the recommendations [6,7]. Once the possibility of ‘false
positive’ results has been ruled out, another important factor that
plays an important role in the definition of ‘true bacteraemia’ is the
blood volume and number of sets collected. The authors did not
calculate the amount of blood in each blood culture bottle, which it
has been clearly related to TTP [8]. Two to four sets of blood
specimens should be collected and each set should consist of 20–40mL
of blood (except for children, which must not exceed 1% of the
patient’s total blood volume) [6]. In situations in which this has not
been properly assessed, false negative blood cultures results may
appear [2]. Besides, another important variable to take into
consideration is the rate of positive blood culture bottles from the
total number of the blood culture bottles withdrawn, which can also
help us to differentiate a true CoNS bacteraemia from contamination.
Some of these issues would explain why in the study of Morioka et al.
they could not reach almost 90% of specificity and sensitivity for
predicting CoNS bacteraemia and contamination, respectively. Many
attempts based on different variables, such as molecular or number of
positive blood culture sets, have been made to try to differentiate
true CoNS bacteraemia from contamination [9–13]. However, one of the
most rapid and easy-to-use method would be that directly based on the
TTP of the blood cultures which, as it has been stated by Morioka et
al. and other authors that also considered clinical criteria, when it
is approximately >20 h, it would be reliable enough for predicting
true CoNS bacteraemia [14–17]. In addition, Garcia-Vazquez et al. also
recommend to use a clinical algorithm to detect a clinically
significant CoNS bacteraemia [18]. In this regard, we consider that an
algorithm combining clinical and microbiological variables, such as
TTP, number of positive blood culture, and volume of blood could be
useful as indicative when diagnosing CoNS bacteraemia in a general
basis.
