AB  - Critical Care Medicine www.ccmjournal.org 439 A 79 year-old woman is
admitted to the ICU with fever, flank pain, and intractable vomiting.
Urinalysis and images of her abdomen and pelvis are consistent with
pyelonephritis. Treated empirically with ceftriaxone, both blood and
urine cultures ultimately grow quinolone-sensitive Escherichia coli.
On hospital day 4, her IV access needs to be replaced per
institutional policy. Nursing is unable to obtain a secondary IV
access, and a peripherally inserted central catheter line is placed.
The patient completes a 14-day course of IV antibiotics for
pyelonephritis. Unfortunately, her hospital stay was complicated by
Clostridium difficile infection and an upper extremity deep vein
thrombosis requiring anticoagulation. Although this fictitious
clinical vignette is not typical of the majority of cases of
bacteremia, every experienced ICU practitioner has encountered such an
unfortunate patient and wondered whether a shorter course of
antibiotics would have resulted in a better outcome with fewer
complications. In this issue of Critical Care Medicine, Daneman et al
(1) have explored the issue of treating bacteremia in the ICU with the
hopes of answering this question. They conducted a large, multicenter
retrospective study of 1,202 Canadian ICU patients with bacteremia
excluding anyone with an infection who required a prolonged antibiotic
course as per established infectious disease (ID) guidelines
(endocarditis, osteomyelitis, etc.). Baseline characteristics were
notable for a relatively low prevalence of highly resistant infections
(approximately 9.5%) and the fact that there were few patients with
chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD) (< 4%). The duration of
therapy was highly variable with a median of 14 days (interquartile
range, 9–17.5). When patients were dichotomized into groups receiving
shorter (≤ 10 d) or longer (> 10 d) antibiotic courses, a few
associations of questionable clinical importance using a multivariable
model were identified although a multitude of patient and pathogen
characteristics were considered. Patients were more likely to receive
a short duration of therapy if they had COPD, if they were burn
patients, if they were infected with coagulase negative staphylococci,
or if the source of infection was undetermined. Survival differences
between shorter and longer duration of therapy were not found despite
the authors using multiple statistical strategies. In essence, when
confounding by indication (addressed with propensity matching) and
survival bias (addressed both by repeating the propensity matched
analysis after successively excluding early deaths, as well as by
using a Cox proportional hazards model) were appropriately accounted
for, no mortality difference between the two treatment groups was
identified. On the basis of these data, it would be unwise to simply
conclude that courses of shorter and longer duration antibiotic
therapy were associated with similar outcomes and that either strategy
could be applied interchangeably in all cases of ICU bacteremia.
Despite propensity matching with 21 variables, it is very likely that
selection bias was not entirely eliminated. Thus, clinicians used
additional information (unmeasured in this study) when considering the
risks of a shorter antibiotic course (treatment failure) versus the
risk of a longer antibiotic course (Clostridium difficile infection,
development of microbial resistance, potential need for central line
access, venous thrombosis, line infection and bacteremia, and
increased cost). Besides highlighting the need for prospective trials,
this study reminds critical care practitioners to seek expert opinion
for managing bacteremia when guidelines and protocols are uncertain or
not available. Both ID and antibiotic stewardship (AS) engagement are
paramount. Nowhere is this more evident than in the treatment of
Staphylococcus aureus bacteremia (SAB) in which management aided by ID
consultation is associated with better adherence to established
standards of care and—more importantly—a mortality benefit (2–4).
